      "content": "Even when controlling for socioeconomic status, the remaining disparities are complex, but most mainstream sociological analysis still frames them within the context of differential treatment. These subtle remaining gaps are often interpreted as outcomes of historical policy impacts, such as residential segregation, which creates distinct social environments. Attributing them purely to inherent, non-contextual \"behavior\" risks echoing the very essentialism you are trying to avoid. The most data-robust view integrates structural context with observed behavior rather than separating them entirely.",
